ResourceHeader.ResourceName: IBEX High Energy Neutral Atom Imager (Hi), Level H3 (H3), Data

RevisionEvent.Note: Initial release of metadata, ADAPT generated, LFB

ResourceHeader.Description: 1: The Interstellar Boundary Explorer (IBEX) has operated in space since 2008 updating our knowledge of the outer heliosphere and its interaction with the local interstellar medium. Start-time: 2008-12-25. There are currently 18 releases of IBEX-HI and IBEX-LO data covering 2009-2022. 2: This data set is from the Release 18 (1 year-cadence) IBEX-Hi map data for the years 2009-2022 in the form of ramdirectional ENA (hydrogen) fluxes with no Compton-Getting correction (nocg) of flux spectra for spacecraft motion and correction for ENA survival probability (sp) between 1 and 100 AU. 3. The data consist of all-sky maps in Solar Ecliptic Longitude (east and west) and Latitude angles for ENA (hydrogen) fluxes from IBEX-Hi energy bands 2-6 in numerical data form. Energy channels 2-6 have FWHM ranges of 0.52-0.95, 0.84-1.55, 1.36-2.50, 1.99-3.75, 3.13-6.00 keV, respectively. The corresponding center-point energies are 0.71, 1.11, 1.74, 2.73, and 4.29 keV. Details of the data and enabled science from Release 10 are given in the following journal publication: 4: McComas, D. J., et al. (2017), Seven Years of Imaging the Global Heliosphere with IBEX, Astrophys. J. Supp. Ser., 229(2), 41 (32 pp.), http://doi.org/10.3847/1538-4365/aa66d8 5. The following codes are used to define dataset types: cg = Compton-Getting corrections have been applied to the data to account for the speed of the spacecraft relative to the direction of arrival of the ENAs. nocg = no Compton-Getting corrections sp = survival probability corrections have been applied to the data to account for the loss of ENAs due to radiation pressure, photoionization and ionization via charge exchange with solar wind protons as they stream through the heliosphere. This correction scales the data out from IBEX at 1 AU to ~100 AU. In the original data this mode is denoted as Tabular. nosp - no survival probability corrections have been applied to the data. omni = data from all directions. ram = data was collected when the spacecraft was ramming into the incoming ENAs. antiram = data was collected when the spacecraft was moving away from the incoming ENAs. mono = mono-energy Compton-Getting corrected maps. gdf = globally distributed flux maps ribbon = ribbon maps 6. The following list associates Release 18 map numbers (1-28) with mission year (1-14), orbits (11-592B), and dates (12/25/2008-12/26/2022): Map 1: year 1, orbits 11-34, dates 12/25/2008-06/25/2009 Map Parameter.Name: Epoch
Parameter.Description: CDF epoch time for the start of the measurement period
Parameter.Caveats: This Parameter exhibits an increasing Monotonic Progression

Parameter.Name: Epoch2
Parameter.Description: CDF epoch time for end of the measurement period
Parameter.Caveats: This Parameter exhibits an increasing Monotonic Progression

Parameter.Name: Map Number
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: Epoch
Parameter.Description: Sequential number for six-month maps from IBEX Data
Parameter.Caveats: Yearly average is calculated over two consecutive maps; this is the starting map number

Parameter.Name: Solar Ecliptic Latitude Bin Number
Parameter.Description: Solar Ecliptic Latitude Bin Number corresponding to six-degree latitudinal increments of the current IBEX-HI viewing sector
Parameter.Caveats: There are 30 angular bins in Solar Ecliptic Latitude ( -90 to +90 degrees). The center-point degree value for Bin 1 is -87 degrees and for Bin 30 is +87 degrees.

Parameter.Name: Solar West Ecliptic Longitude Bin Number
Parameter.Description: Solar West Ecliptic Longitude Bin Number corresponding to six-degree longitudinal increments of the current IBEX-HI viewing sector
Parameter.Caveats: There are 60 angular sectors in Solar West Ecliptic Longitude from 0 to 360 degrees. The first Number Bin = 1 corresponds to a mid-point longitude angle of 3 degrees, the last = 30 to 357 degrees.

Parameter.Name: Solar Ecliptic Latitude
Parameter.Caveats: Latitude value corresponds to the mid-point of six-degree latitudinal IBEX-HI viewing sector

Parameter.Name: Solar West Ecliptic Longitude
Parameter.Caveats: Longitude value corresponds to the mid-point of six-degree longitudinal IBEX-HI viewing sector.

Parameter.Name: Solar East Ecliptic Longitude
Parameter.Caveats: Longitude value corresponds to the mid-point of six-degree longitudinal IBEX-HI viewing sector.

Parameter.Name: Starting Orbit Number
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: Epoch
Parameter.Description: Starting Orbit Number of the measurement period
Parameter.Caveats: IBEX orbital period around Earth is 7.5 days.

Parameter.Name: Ending Orbit Number
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: Epoch
Parameter.Description: Ending Orbit Number of the measurement period
Parameter.Caveats: IBEX orbital period around Earth is 7.5 days
